{
  "answer": "**I was unable to locate a maqta (the concluding couplet of a ghazal where the poet typically inserts his takhallus \"Zauq\") that explicitly names Zauq in connection to the Mughal court of Bahadur Shah (also known as Zafar) within the English translations of *Diwan-E-Zauq*.**\n\nThe Falsafa corpus includes *Diwan-E-Zauq* (*sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798*), a collection of 60 ghazals by Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq (1789–1848), the renowned court poet (*shā'ir-e-ā'in* or *shā'ir-e-lāḥore*) of the last Mughal emperor, Bahadur Shah II.[^1] Each chapter is a separate ghazal in verse layout, with available variants: original (Urdu script), transliteration (Roman Urdu), and translation (English prose poetry).\n\nSearches across the English bodies for distinctive phrases like \"Zauq Bahadur,\" \"Zauq Zafar,\" \"Bahadur Shah,\" \"Zauq Mughal,\" \"Zauq court,\" \"badshah,\" \"padshah,\" \"shah,\" \"darbar,\" \"king,\" \"emperor,\" and variations (including exact \"Zauq\" and work-specific filters) returned no matches in this work.[^2] \"Zauq\" does appear as the takhallus in at least one maqta—for example, the final couplet of ghazal #5:\n\n> Ah Zauq, I fell, and clutched my heart, its every door ajar,  \n> when she just stood, with such a grace, and on her hip she laid a hand.[^3]\n\nHowever, this (and other identifiable maqtas) lacks any reference to the Mughal court, Bahadur Shah, or related imperial imagery.\n\nThe corpus's English translations may poeticize or omit historical proper names/references common in classical Urdu ghazals, focusing on universal themes of love, longing, and mysticism. Zauq's courtly status is noted in the work's metadata,[^4] but no translated maqta ties his takhallus directly to Bahadur Shah's *darbar*. If this refers to a specific Urdu-original couplet (e.g., potentially boasting his position), it does not surface in the searchable English texts. The corpus covers 37 works; not every nuance or variant is included. For the original Urdu, consult a full critical edition outside this collection.",
